storical criticism, and medievalism. The contributors, trailblazing international specialists in their respective fields, honour Trigg's distinctive and energetic mode of enquiry (the symptomatic long history) and intellectual contribution to the humanities. At the same time, their approaches exemplify shifting trends in Chaucer scholarship. Like Chaucer's pilgrims, these scholars speak to and alongside each other, but their essays are also attentive to 'hearing Chaucer speak' then, now and in the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAlliterative Verse.  aChaucer Redactions.  aChaucer, Geoffrey.  aEcocriticism.  aEmotions in Literature.  aEmotions, History.  aFace in Literature.  aFifteenth-century Caxton.  aGeoffrey Chaucer.  aMedieval Literature.  aMedieval Romance.  aMedievalism.  aMiddle English Literature.  aNineteenth-century medievalism.  aStephanie Trigg.  aTrigg, Stephanie.1 aCohen, Jeffrey Jerome, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDownes, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD’Arcens, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGanim, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrady, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHickey, Helen M, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHickey, Helen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKnight, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab